      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-03",
      "text": "The only constant in life is change.",
      "author": "Heraclitus",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Ancient",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "flux",
        "ontology",
        "change"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-04",
      "text": "What is, is.",
      "author": "Parmenides",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Ancient",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "being",
        "absolutism",
        "contrast-heraclitus"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-05",
      "text": "You have power over your mind \u2014 not outside events.",
      "author": "Marcus Aurelius",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "stoic",
        "sovereignty",
        "interior"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-06",
      "text": "It's not what happens to you, but how you react to it that matters.",
      "author": "Epictetus",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "stoic",
        "agency",
        "reaction"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-01",
      "text": "It is better to be feared than loved, if you cannot be both.",
      "author": "Niccol\u00f2 Machiavelli",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "politics",
        "realism",
        "prince"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-02",
      "text": "The life of man [is] solitary, poor, nasty, brutish, and short.",
      "author": "Thomas Hobbes",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "void",
      "tags": [
        "state",
        "chaos",
        "security"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-03",
      "text": "Where there is no law, there is no freedom.",
      "author": "John Locke",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "justice",
      "tags": [
        "rights",
        "liberty",
        "contrast-hobbes"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-04",
      "text": "Act only according to that maxim whereby you can, at the same time, will that it should become a universal law.",
      "author": "Immanuel Kant",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "justice",
      "tags": [
        "moral",
        "categorical",
        "imperative"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-05",
      "text": "Reason is, and ought only to be the slave of the passions.",
      "author": "David Hume",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "empiricism",
        "skepticism",
        "contrast-kant"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-01",
      "text": "He who has a why to live can bear almost any how.",
      "author": "Friedrich Nietzsche",
      "civilization": "Modern_Political",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "will",
        "existential",
        "meaning"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-02",
      "text": "Life can only be understood backwards; but it must be lived forwards.",
      "author": "S\u00f8ren Kierkegaard",
      "civilization": "Modern_Political",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "existential",
        "time",
        "leap"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-03",
      "text": "Philosophers have only interpreted the world; the point, however, is to change it.",
      "author": "Karl Marx",
      "civilization": "Modern_Political",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "materialism",
        "action",
        "determinism"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "CG-01",
      "text": "The sad truth is that most evil is done by people who never make up their minds to be good or evil.",
      "author": "Hannah Arendt",
      "civilization": "Contemporary_Global",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "evil",
        "banality",
        "responsibility"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-04",
      "text": "Nearly all men can stand adversity, but if you want to test a man's character, give him power.",
      "author": "Abraham Lincoln",
      "civilization": "Modern_Political",
      "era": "Industrial",
      "category": "justice",
      "tags": [
        "power",
        "character",
        "restraint"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-01",
      "text": "The most incomprehensible thing about the universe is that it is comprehensible.",
      "author": "Albert Einstein",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "science",
        "wonder",
        "universe"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-02",
      "text": "What we observe is not nature itself, but nature exposed to our method of questioning.",
      "author": "Werner Heisenberg",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "uncertainty",
        "quantum",
        "observation"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-03",
      "text": "Either mathematics is too big for the human mind, or the human mind is more than a machine.",
      "author": "Kurt G\u00f6del",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "logic",
        "incompleteness",
        "mind"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-04",
      "text": "We can only see a short distance ahead, but we can see plenty there that needs to be done.",
      "author": "Alan Turing",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "computation",
        "future",
        "action"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-05",
      "text": "Information is the resolution of uncertainty.",
      "author": "Claude Shannon",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "information",
        "entropy",
        "communication"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-06",
      "text": "I would rather have questions that can't be answered than answers that can't be questioned.",
      "author": "Richard Feynman",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "science",
        "questions",
        "skepticism"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-07",
      "text": "Somewhere, something incredible is waiting to be known.",
      "author": "Carl Sagan",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "cosmos",
        "discovery",
        "humility"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-06",
      "text": "The heart has its reasons which reason knows nothing of.",
      "author": "Blaise Pascal",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "faith",
        "reason",
        "wager"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "CG-02",
      "text": "Attention is the rarest and purest form of generosity.",
      "author": "Simone Weil",
      "civilization": "Contemporary_Global",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "justice",
      "tags": [
        "attention",
        "ethics",
        "presence"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "CG-03",
      "text": "The real test of a man is not how he behaves in moments of comfort, but how he stands at times of controversy and challenge.",
      "author": "Vaclav Havel",
      "civilization": "Contemporary_Global",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "truth",
        "power",
        "dissent"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "CG-04",
      "text": "Resentment is like drinking poison and then hoping it will kill your enemies.",
      "author": "Nelson Mandela",
      "civilization": "African_Civilizations",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "forgiveness",
        "freedom",
        "reconciliation"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "CG-05",
      "text": "Injustice anywhere is a threat to justice everywhere.",
      "author": "Martin Luther King Jr.",
      "civilization": "Contemporary_Global",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "justice",
      "tags": [
        "rights",
        "equality",
        "universal"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-08",
      "text": "Nothing in life is to be feared, it is only to be understood.",
      "author": "Marie Curie",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Industrial",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "science",
        "courage",
        "discovery"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "SE-01",
      "text": "DITEMPA, BUKAN DIBERI.",
      "author": "Arif Fazil",
      "civilization": "Contemporary_Global",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "seal",
      "tags": [
        "forged",
        "seal",
        "motto",
        "arifos"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 4
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-09",
      "text": "In any consistent formal system, there are statements that are true but unprovable.",
      "author": "Kurt G\u00f6del",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "void",
      "tags": [
        "incompleteness",
        "logic",
        "limits"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-10",
      "text": "The concept of truth cannot be defined within the language to which it applies.",
      "author": "Alfred Tarski",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "semantics",
        "truth",
        "meta"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-11",
      "text": "The whole problem with the world is that fools and fanatics are always so certain of themselves.",
      "author": "Bertrand Russell",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "certainty",
        "doubt",
        "fanaticism"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-12",
      "text": "Whereof one cannot speak, thereof one must be silent.",
      "author": "Ludwig Wittgenstein",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "void",
      "tags": [
        "silence",
        "limits",
        "language"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-13",
      "text": "The limits of my language mean the limits of my world.",
      "author": "Ludwig Wittgenstein",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "language",
        "world",
        "silence"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-14",
      "text": "Science must begin with myths, and with the criticism of myths.",
      "author": "Karl Popper",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "science",
        "falsification",
        "myth"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-15",
      "text": "Normal science does not aim at novelties of fact or theory and, when successful, finds none.",
      "author": "Thomas Kuhn",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "paradigm",
        "normal",
        "revolution"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-16",
      "text": "Research programmes may be progressive or degenerating.",
      "author": "Imre Lakatos",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "science",
        "progress",
        "degeneration"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-17",
      "text": "The only principle that does not inhibit progress is: anything goes.",
      "author": "Paul Feyerabend",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "anarchism",
        "method",
        "science"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-18",
      "text": "Instead of trying to produce a programme to simulate the adult mind, why not rather try to produce one which simulates the child's?",
      "author": "Alan Turing",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "ai",
        "learning",
        "child"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-19",
      "text": "Anyone who considers arithmetical methods of producing random digits is, of course, in a state of sin.",
      "author": "John von Neumann",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "random",
        "sin",
        "computation"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-20",
      "text": "You cannot prove that a program is elegant.",
      "author": "Gregory Chaitin",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "void",
      "tags": [
        "elegance",
        "proof",
        "limits"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-21",
      "text": "The fundamental problem of communication is that of reproducing at one point either exactly or approximately a message selected at another point.",
      "author": "Claude Shannon",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "information",
        "communication",
        "channel"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-22",
      "text": "We are but whirlpools in a river of ever-flowing water.",
      "author": "Norbert Wiener",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "cybernetics",
        "flow",
        "identity"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-23",
      "text": "Order out of chaos.",
      "author": "Ilya Prigogine",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "entropy",
        "dissipative",
        "structure"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "MS-24",
      "text": "The absence of evidence is not evidence of absence.",
      "author": "Nassim Nicholas Taleb",
      "civilization": "Modern_Scientific",
      "era": "Contemporary",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "black",
        "swan",
        "evidence"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-07",
      "text": "I think, therefore I am.",
      "author": "Ren\u00e9 Descartes",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "truth",
      "tags": [
        "cogito",
        "existence",
        "certainty"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-08",
      "text": "Freedom is understanding necessity.",
      "author": "Baruch Spinoza",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "freedom",
        "necessity",
        "ethics"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-09",
      "text": "Man is equally incapable of seeing the nothingness from which he emerges and the infinity in which he is engulfed.",
      "author": "Blaise Pascal",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "void",
      "tags": [
        "infinity",
        "nothingness",
        "terror"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-10",
      "text": "Man can do what he wills but he cannot will what he wills.",
      "author": "Arthur Schopenhauer",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "will",
        "determinism",
        "freedom"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-05",
      "text": "The curious task of economics is to demonstrate to men how little they really know about what they imagine they can design.",
      "author": "Friedrich Hayek",
      "civilization": "Modern_Political",
      "era": "Modern",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "economics",
        "knowledge",
        "design"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "MP-06",
      "text": "There is only one way to avoid criticism: do nothing, say nothing, and be nothing.",
      "author": "Aristotle",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "criticism",
        "action",
        "virtue"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AE-04",
      "text": "Knowing others is intelligence; knowing yourself is true wisdom.",
      "author": "Laozi",
      "civilization": "Ancient_East",
      "era": "Ancient",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "self",
        "knowledge",
        "tao"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "AE-05",
      "text": "The man who asks a question is a fool for a minute, the man who does not ask is a fool for life.",
      "author": "Confucius",
      "civilization": "Ancient_East",
      "era": "Ancient",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "question",
        "fool",
        "learning"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "AE-06",
      "text": "In the midst of chaos, there is also opportunity.",
      "author": "Sun Tzu",
      "civilization": "Ancient_East",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "chaos",
        "opportunity",
        "strategy"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-07",
      "text": "We are what we repeatedly do. Excellence, then, is not an act, but a habit.",
      "author": "Aristotle",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "discipline",
      "tags": [
        "habit",
        "excellence",
        "virtue"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-08",
      "text": "The unexamined life is not worth living.",
      "author": "Socrates",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "examination",
        "life",
        "worth"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-09",
      "text": "Fortune favors the bold.",
      "author": "Virgil",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "power",
      "tags": [
        "fortune",
        "bold",
        "courage"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 3
    },
    {
      "id": "AW-10",
      "text": "A room without books is like a body without a soul.",
      "author": "Cicero",
      "civilization": "Ancient_West",
      "era": "Classical",
      "category": "wisdom",
      "tags": [
        "books",
        "soul",
        "knowledge"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-11",
      "text": "Man is born free, and everywhere he is in chains.",
      "author": "Jean-Jacques Rousseau",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
      "era": "Enlightenment",
      "category": "paradox",
      "tags": [
        "freedom",
        "chains",
        "society"
      ],
      "g_star_band": 0
    },
    {
      "id": "EE-12",
      "text": "Hell is other people.",
      "author": "Jean-Paul Sartre",
      "civilization": "European_Enlightenment",
